 Serverless Container Orchestration with Amazon ECS Fargate
Objectives
Design and deploy a production-grade containerized Node.js service to Amazon ECS using the Fargate launch type (a serverless compute engine that removes the need to manage EC2 instances)
Implement Application Auto Scaling policies driven by CloudWatch metrics to maintain service availability under variable load
Construct a CloudWatch observability stack √¢¬Ä¬î dashboards, alarms, and Log Insights queries √¢¬Ä¬î that surfaces container-level health signals
Prerequisites
Comfort with Linux command-line operations including file editing, environment variables, and shell scripting
Conceptual understanding of Docker image layering, container networking, and HTTP request/response cycles
Familiarity with AWS IAM concepts: roles, trust policies, and managed policies
Lab Environment
You will work on a dedicated AWS EC2 Ubuntu instance provided by Al Nafi. The instance has a base Ubuntu installation; you will install all required tools in Task 1.

Task 1: Environment Setup √¢¬Ä¬î Install and Verify All Required Tools
Your instance has no pre-installed tooling. You must install Docker Engine, the AWS CLI v2, and supporting utilities, then verify each before proceeding.

Step 1.1: Install Docker Engine and the AWS CLI v2
Install Docker Engine from Docker's official apt repository. The keyring approach below pins the repository to a verified GPG key so future apt upgrade runs pull only authenticated packages.

sudo apt-get update -y
sudo apt-get install -y ca-certificates curl gnupg lsb-release

sudo install -m 0755 -d /etc/apt/keyrings

curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg \
  | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg

sudo chmod a+r /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg
Official guide if the URL above changes: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/

sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list <<'EOF'
deb [arch=amd64 signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu jammy stable
EOF

sudo apt-get update -y
sudo apt-get install -y docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io

sudo usermod -aG docker "$USER"
newgrp docker
Troubleshoot this step:

Error seen: E: Malformed entry 1 in list file /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list √¢¬Ä¬î this means the file contains a literal backslash or newline artifact.
Recovery: cat /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list √¢¬Ä¬î the file must be a single unbroken line; delete it with sudo rm /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list and recreate using the heredoc above.
Official reference: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/
Now install the AWS CLI v2:

curl -fsSL "https://awscli.amazonaws.com/awscli-exe-linux-x86_64.zip" -o /tmp/awscliv2.zip
Official guide if the URL above changes: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/getting-started-install.html

sudo apt-get install -y unzip
unzip /tmp/awscliv2.zip -d /tmp/awscliv2-extracted
sudo /tmp/awscliv2-extracted/aws/install
Troubleshoot this step:

Error seen: curl: (22) The requested URL returned error: 403 or a file named awscliv2.zip that is actually an HTML error page (unzip will report End-of-central-directory signature not found).
Recovery: Run file /tmp/awscliv2.zip √¢¬Ä¬î if it reports HTML document rather than Zip archive data, the download URL has changed; retrieve the current URL from the official guide below.
Official reference: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/getting-started-install.html
