Task 2: Build a Production Container Image and Publish It to ECR
Amazon Elastic Container Registry (ECR) is a fully managed Docker registry. ECS Fargate pulls your image from ECR at task launch time; the image must be present in ECR before you register a task definition.

Step 2.1: Implement the Application and Dockerfile
Design a stateless Node.js HTTP service that satisfies all of the following constraints:

Exposes three routes: GET / returns a JSON payload including the container hostname; GET /health returns HTTP 200 with a JSON body containing status, uptime, and timestamp; GET /metrics returns process.memoryUsage() and process.cpuUsage() as JSON
Runs as a non-root OS user inside the container
Declares a Dockerfile HEALTHCHECK instruction that polls GET /health every 30 seconds with a 3-second timeout and 3 retries
Uses a multi-stage or minimal base image (Alpine-based Node 18 is acceptable) to keep the final image under 150 MB
Accepts the listening port from the environment variable PORT, defaulting to 3000 if unset
Your application must conform to this interface contract:

interface HealthResponse {
  status: "healthy" | "degraded";
  uptime: number;          // seconds, from process.uptime()
  timestamp: string;       // ISO 8601
}

interface RootResponse {
  message: string;
  container_id: string;    // os.hostname()
  timestamp: string;
}

interface MetricsResponse {
  memory: NodeJS.MemoryUsage;
  cpu: NodeJS.CpuUsage;
}
Build the image locally and confirm it starts cleanly:

docker build -t fargate-web-app:v1 .
docker run --rm -d -p 3000:3000 --name test-app fargate-web-app:v1
sleep 5
curl -sf http://localhost:3000/health
docker stop test-app
Confirmation: curl returns a JSON body with "status": "healthy" and a non-zero uptime.

Step 2.2: Create an ECR Repository, Tag, and Push the Image
Create the ECR repository, authenticate Docker to it, and push two tags (latest and v1). All commands below are parameterised so they run without editing.

REGION="us-east-1"
ACCOUNT_ID=$(aws sts get-caller-identity --query Account --output text)

aws ecr create-repository \
  --repository-name fargate-web-app \
  --image-scanning-configuration scanOnPush=true \
  --region "$REGION"

REPO_URI=$(aws ecr describe-repositories \
  --repository-names fargate-web-app \
  --query 'repositories[0].repositoryUri' \
  --output text)

echo "REPO_URI=$REPO_URI"
aws ecr get-login-password --region "$REGION" \
  | docker login --username AWS --password-stdin "$REPO_URI"

docker tag fargate-web-app:v1 "$REPO_URI:latest"
docker tag fargate-web-app:v1 "$REPO_URI:v1"

docker push "$REPO_URI:latest"
docker push "$REPO_URI:v1"

aws ecr list-images --repository-name fargate-web-app --region "$REGION"
Confirmation: aws ecr list-images returns two entries with imageTag values latest and v1.

Troubleshoot this step:

Error seen: no basic auth credentials or authorization token has expired when pushing.
Recovery: Re-run the aws ecr get-login-password ... | docker login ... command √¢¬Ä¬î ECR tokens expire after 12 hours; you must re-authenticate before each push session.
Official reference: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECR/latest/userguide/registry_auth.html
Task 3: Deploy, Scale, and Observe the Service on ECS Fargate
Step 3.1: Provision IAM Roles, the ECS Cluster, and the Fargate Task Definition
ECS Fargate requires two distinct IAM roles: the task execution role (used by the Fargate control plane to pull images from ECR and write logs to CloudWatch) and the task role (assumed by your application code at runtime). Create both, then register a task definition that references them.

Your task definition must satisfy these architectural constraints:

Launch type: FARGATE; network mode: awsvpc (each task receives its own elastic network interface)
CPU: 256 units (0.25 vCPU); memory: 512 MiB √¢¬Ä¬î sufficient for the sample workload
Log driver: awslogs writing to the log group /ecs/fargate-web-app with a 7-day retention policy
Container health check mirrors the Dockerfile HEALTHCHECK (polls /health, 30-second interval, 5-second timeout, 3 retries, 60-second start period)
Environment variable NODE_ENV=production and PORT=3000 injected at the task level
REGION="us-east-1"
ACCOUNT_ID=$(aws sts get-caller-identity --query Account --output text)
REPO_URI=$(aws ecr describe-repositories \
  --repository-names fargate-web-app \
  --query 'repositories[0].repositoryUri' \
  --output text)

# Create the CloudWatch log group before registering the task definition
aws logs create-log-group \
  --log-group-name /ecs/fargate-web-app \
  --region "$REGION"

aws logs put-retention-policy \
  --log-group-name /ecs/fargate-web-app \
  --retention-in-days 7
Create the task execution role trust policy and attach the AWS-managed policy:

cat > /tmp/ecs-trust-policy.json <<'EOF'
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Principal": { "Service": "ecs-tasks.amazonaws.com" },
      "Action": "sts:AssumeRole"
    }
  ]
}
EOF

aws iam create-role \
  --role-name ecsTaskExecutionRole \
  --assume-role-policy-document file:///tmp/ecs-trust-policy.json

aws iam attach-role-policy \
  --role-name ecsTaskExecutionRole \
  --policy-arn arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/service-role/AmazonECSTaskExecutionRolePolicy

aws iam create-role \
  --role-name ecsTaskRole \
  --assume-role-policy-document file:///tmp/ecs-trust-policy.json
Create and attach a least-privilege CloudWatch Logs policy to the task role:

cat > /tmp/cw-logs-policy.json <<'EOF'
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "logs:CreateLogStream",
        "logs:PutLogEvents",
        "logs:DescribeLogStreams"
      ],
      "Resource": "arn:aws:logs:*:*:log-group:/ecs/fargate-web-app:*"
    }
  ]
}
EOF

aws iam create-policy \
  --policy-name ECSTaskCloudWatchLogsPolicy \
  --policy-document file:///tmp/cw-logs-policy.json

aws iam attach-role-policy \
  --role-name ecsTaskRole \
  --policy-arn "arn:aws:iam::${ACCOUNT_ID}:policy/ECSTaskCloudWatchLogsPolicy"
Create the ECS cluster and register the task definition. The heredoc below writes the full JSON in one pass with no line-continuation characters:

aws ecs create-cluster \
  --cluster-name fargate-lab-cluster \
  --capacity-providers FARGATE \
  --default-capacity-provider-strategy capacityProvider=FARGATE,weight=1 \
  --region "$REGION"
cat > /tmp/task-definition.json <<EOF
{
  "family": "fargate-web-app-task",
  "networkMode": "awsvpc",
  "requiresCompatibilities": ["FARGATE"],
  "cpu": "256",
  "memory": "512",
  "executionRoleArn": "arn:aws:iam::${ACCOUNT_ID}:role/ecsTaskExecutionRole",
  "taskRoleArn": "arn:aws:iam::${ACCOUNT_ID}:role/ecsTaskRole",
  "containerDefinitions": [
    {
      "name": "web-app",
      "image": "${REPO_URI}:latest",
      "essential": true,
      "portMappings": [
        { "containerPort": 3000, "protocol": "tcp" }
      ],
      "environment": [
        { "name": "NODE_ENV", "value": "production" },
        { "name": "PORT",     "value": "3000" }
      ],
      "logConfiguration": {
        "logDriver": "awslogs",
        "options": {
          "awslogs-group":         "/ecs/fargate-web-app",
          "awslogs-region":        "${REGION}",
          "awslogs-stream-prefix": "ecs"
        }
      },
      "healthCheck": {
        "command":     ["CMD-SHELL", "curl -sf http://localhost:3000/health || exit 1"],
        "interval":    30,
        "timeout":     5,
        "retries":     3,
        "startPeriod": 60
      }
    }
  ]
}
EOF

aws ecs register-task-definition \
  --cli-input-json file:///tmp/task-definition.json \
  --region "$REGION"
Confirmation: aws ecs describe-task-definition --task-definition fargate-web-app-task returns a definition with status: ACTIVE.

Step 3.2: Launch an ECS Service with Auto Scaling and CloudWatch Observability
Deploy the task as an ECS service (a long-running managed group of tasks) rather than a one-off run-task call, so that Fargate automatically replaces failed tasks and Application Auto Scaling can adjust the desired count.

Networking constraints:

Use the default VPC and any one of its public subnets
Create a dedicated security group that allows inbound TCP on port 3000 from 0.0.0.0/0 and unrestricted outbound (required for ECR and CloudWatch API calls)
Set assignPublicIp=ENABLED so tasks are reachable without a NAT gateway
VPC_ID=$(aws ec2 describe-vpcs \
  --filters "Name=isDefault,Values=true" \
  --query 'Vpcs[0].VpcId' \
  --output text)

SUBNET_ID=$(aws ec2 describe-subnets \
  --filters "Name=vpc-id,Values=${VPC_ID}" \
  --query 'Subnets[0].SubnetId' \
  --output text)

SG_ID=$(aws ec2 create-security-group \
  --group-name fargate-web-app-sg \
  --description "Fargate web app inbound 3000" \
  --vpc-id "$VPC_ID" \
  --query 'GroupId' \
  --output text)

aws ec2 authorize-security-group-ingress \
  --group-id "$SG_ID" \
  --protocol tcp \
  --port 3000 \
  --cidr 0.0.0.0/0

echo "SG_ID=$SG_ID  SUBNET_ID=$SUBNET_ID"
Create the ECS service with a desired count of 2 (so you can observe load distribution):

cat > /tmp/service-definition.json <<EOF
{
  "serviceName":    "fargate-web-app-service",
  "cluster":        "fargate-lab-cluster",
  "taskDefinition": "fargate-web-app-task",
  "desiredCount":   2,
  "launchType":     "FARGATE",
  "networkConfiguration": {
    "awsvpcConfiguration": {
      "subnets":        ["${SUBNET_ID}"],
      "securityGroups": ["${SG_ID}"],
      "assignPublicIp": "ENABLED"
    }
  },
  "deploymentConfiguration": {
    "maximumPercent":        200,
    "minimumHealthyPercent": 50
  },
  "healthCheckGracePeriodSeconds": 60
}
EOF

aws ecs create-service \
  --cli-input-json file:///tmp/service-definition.json \
  --region "$REGION"

aws ecs wait services-stable \
  --cluster fargate-lab-cluster \
  --services fargate-web-app-service \
  --region "$REGION"
Register the service as an Application Auto Scaling target and attach a CPU-based target-tracking policy (target: 70% average CPU, scale-out cooldown 300 s, scale-in cooldown 300 s) and a memory-based target-tracking policy (target: 80% average memory). Minimum capacity: 1 task; maximum capacity: 6 tasks.

aws application-autoscaling register-scalable-target \
  --service-namespace ecs \
  --resource-id "service/fargate-lab-cluster/fargate-web-app-service" \
  --scalable-dimension ecs:service:DesiredCount \
  --min-capacity 1 \
  --max-capacity 6
cat > /tmp/cpu-scaling-policy.json <<'EOF'
{
  "PolicyName":        "cpu-target-tracking",
  "ServiceNamespace":  "ecs",
  "ResourceId":        "service/fargate-lab-cluster/fargate-web-app-service",
  "ScalableDimension": "ecs:service:DesiredCount",
  "PolicyType":        "TargetTrackingScaling",
  "TargetTrackingScalingPolicyConfiguration": {
    "TargetValue": 70.0,
    "PredefinedMetricSpecification": {
      "PredefinedMetricType": "ECSServiceAverageCPUUtilization"
    },
    "ScaleOutCooldown": 300,
    "ScaleInCooldown":  300
  }
}
EOF

aws application-autoscaling put-scaling-policy \
  --cli-input-json file:///tmp/cpu-scaling-policy.json
cat > /tmp/mem-scaling-policy.json <<'EOF'
{
  "PolicyName":        "memory-target-tracking",
  "ServiceNamespace":  "ecs",
  "ResourceId":        "service/fargate-lab-cluster/fargate-web-app-service",
  "ScalableDimension": "ecs:service:DesiredCount",
  "PolicyType":        "TargetTrackingScaling",
  "TargetTrackingScalingPolicyConfiguration": {
    "TargetValue": 80.0,
    "PredefinedMetricSpecification": {
      "PredefinedMetricType": "ECSServiceAverageMemoryUtilization"
    },
    "ScaleOutCooldown": 300,
    "ScaleInCooldown":  300
  }
}
EOF

aws application-autoscaling put-scaling-policy \
  --cli-input-json file:///tmp/mem-scaling-policy.json
Create two CloudWatch alarms √¢¬Ä¬î one for CPU above 80% and one for memory above 85% √¢¬Ä¬î each evaluated over two consecutive 5-minute periods. Then create a CloudWatch dashboard named ECS-Fargate-Lab that plots CPUUtilization, MemoryUtilization, RunningTaskCount, and DesiredCount for the service.

Finally, retrieve the public IP of one running task and confirm the application responds:

TASK_ARN=$(aws ecs list-tasks \
  --cluster fargate-lab-cluster \
  --service-name fargate-web-app-service \
  --query 'taskArns[0]' \
  --output text)

PUBLIC_IP=$(aws ecs describe-tasks \
  --cluster fargate-lab-cluster \
  --tasks "$TASK_ARN" \
  --query 'tasks[0].attachments[0].details[?name==`publicIPv4Address`].value' \
  --output text)

echo "Task public IP: $PUBLIC_IP"
curl -sf "http://${PUBLIC_IP}:3000/health"
curl -sf "http://${PUBLIC_IP}:3000/"
Confirmation: Both curl calls return valid JSON; aws ecs describe-services --cluster fargate-lab-cluster --services fargate-web-app-service shows runningCount: 2 and desiredCount: 2; the CloudWatch dashboard is visible in the AWS Console under CloudWatch > Dashboards.

