Expected Outcomes
Two Fargate tasks run concurrently in the fargate-lab-cluster, each responding to HTTP requests on port 3000 with the correct JSON payloads, and CloudWatch Log Insights shows live container stdout entries under /ecs/fargate-web-app.
Application Auto Scaling policies are active and the CloudWatch dashboard displays real-time CPUUtilization and MemoryUtilization metrics for the ECS service.
Troubleshooting
If a task transitions to STOPPED immediately after launch, what specific fields in aws ecs describe-tasks and in the CloudWatch log stream would tell you whether the failure originated in image pull, container startup, or the health check √¢¬Ä¬î and how would you distinguish between them?
If curl to the task's public IP times out but the task shows RUNNING and HEALTHY in ECS, which layer of the network path (security group rules, subnet route table, task ENI assignment, or application bind address) would you inspect first, and what command would you run to confirm or rule out each layer?
Conclusion
This lab demonstrated how ECS Fargate decouples container orchestration from infrastructure management: you defined compute requirements in a task definition and Fargate provisioned, networked, and monitored the underlying capacity invisibly. Pairing Fargate with Application Auto Scaling and CloudWatch produces a self-healing, observable service that adjusts capacity in response to real workload signals rather than static thresholds. These patterns √¢¬Ä¬î immutable images in ECR, least-privilege IAM roles, target-tracking scaling, and structured log routing √¢¬Ä¬î form the operational baseline for production-grade serverless container workloads on AWS.
